<div id="review_2723960767" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2723960767" />
    <a title="Nurul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13323420-nurul"><img alt="Nurul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493970689p2/13323420.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2723960767?book_show_action=true">Feb 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nurul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nurul" href="/user/show/13323420-nurul">Nurul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2723960767" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3733413102185353640">When a murder happened, the focus is always on the victim and the murderer. Who? How? Where? Ooo poor lady... Rarely we think the effect of such tragedy to the family and close friends. How they are forced into the unwanted attention and emotional chaos. Even if we do talk about them, we are just bystanders who express our sympathy as a courtesy. So, this book gave me insight as it explores how a mother finds a closure after losing her daughter.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


